What you need to know:  Starting in the morning section, Mutahi who said beginning on the back nine gave him a good chance of making some birdies, fired his first birdie of the tournament on the par five10th, dropped shots on the 11th, 12th and 15th, but managed to recover at the 14th , 16th and 17thOf the the Kenyans who teed off in the morning, Greg Snow finished on level par 71, while Simon Ngige and the senior pro Dismas Indiza were on one over par 72 eachMeanwhile, the South African Mostert, who like Mutahi, started from the back nine, was also on fire right from the word-go, as he picked up birdies on the first three holes (10, 11, 12) and remained in firm control up to the 16th where he went four under, before closing the nine with a birdie at the 18th